      q: 'Describe how Rutherford\'s alpha-scattering experiment provided evidence for the nuclear model of the atom, and explain the conclusions drawn from the observed scattering pattern.',
      marks: 12, command: 'Describe',
      modelAnswer: 'In Rutherford\'s experiment, alpha particles from a radioactive source were directed at a thin gold foil, and a movable detector recorded their angular distribution after scattering. Most particles passed through the foil with little deflection, showing that atoms are mostly empty space. A small fraction were deflected through large angles, and a very small fraction bounced back almost in the direction they came from — about 1 in 8 000 was deflected by more than 90°. The plum-pudding model could not account for these large deflections, because a uniformly distributed positive charge would not produce strong enough fields to repel the high-energy alpha particles. Rutherford concluded that the positive charge of an atom must be concentrated in a tiny, dense, central nucleus that contained almost all the mass; electrons must orbit this nucleus at relatively large distances, leaving most of the atom as empty space. From the closest approach distance of the bounced-back particles, an upper bound on the radius of the nucleus could be calculated, of order 10⁻¹⁵ m. This evidence forced the replacement of the plum-pudding model with the nuclear model, a foundation of modern atomic physics.'
